{"parse":{"title":"sister","pageid":4486,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Sister}}\n==English==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|en|:inh|enm:suster|tree=1|text=:ine-pro}}\n\n{{doublet|en|soror}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|sister}}, {{m|sco|syster||sister}}, {{cog|fy|sus}}, {{m|fy|suster||sister}}, {{cog|nl|zuster||sister}}, {{cog|de|Schwester||sister}}, {{cog|nb|søster||sister}}, {{cog|nn|-}} and {{cog|sv|syster||sister}}, {{cog|is|systir||sister}}, {{cog|got|𐍃𐍅𐌹𐍃𐍄𐌰𐍂||sister}}, {{cog|la|soror||sister}}, {{cog|ru|сестра́||sister}}, {{cog|lt|sesuo||sister}}, {{cog|sq|vajzë||girl, maiden}}, {{cog|sa|स्वसृ||sister|tr=svásṛ}}, {{cog|fa|خواهر||sister|tr=xâhar}}.\n\nIn standard English, the form with ''i'' is due to contamination with {{cog|non|systir||sister}}.\n\n<!--Moved from [[sistren]].-->The plural ''[[sistren]]'' is from {{inh|en|enm|sistren}}, a variant plural of {{m|enm|sister}}, {{m|enm|suster|t=sister}}; compare {{m|en|brethren}}.\n\nThe sense for \"{{taxfmt|Adelpha|genus}}-genus butterfly\" is a {{semantic loan|nocap=1|en|mul|Adelpha}}, itself from {{cog|grc|ἀδελφή|t=sister}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈsɪs.tə(ɹ)/|a=UK}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-sister.ogg|a=UK}}\n* {{enPR|sĭs'tər|a=GA}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈsɪs.tɚ/}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Naomi Persephone Amethyst (NaomiAmethyst)-sister.wav|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-sister.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɪstə(ɹ)|s=2}}\n* {{homophones|en|cister|cyster}}\n* {{hyphenation|en|sis|ter}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|s|sistren<l:<<archaic>> in most senses>}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q595094}}A [[daughter]] of the same parents as another person; a female [[sibling]].\n#: {{syn|en|sis|qq1=slang}}\n#: {{ant|en|brother}}\n#: {{hyper|en|sibling}}\n#: {{ux|en|My '''sister''' is always driving me crazy.}}\n# A female member of a [[religious order]]; especially one devoted to more active [[service]]; {{lb|en|informally}} a [[nun]].\n#: {{syn|en|nun}}\n#: {{cot|en|brother|friar|frater}}\n#: {{ux|en|Michelle left behind her bank job and became a '''sister''' at the local convent.}}\n# Any butterfly in the [[genus]] {{taxfmt|Adelpha|genus}}, so named for the resemblance of the dark-colored wings to the black [[habit]] traditionally worn by [[nun]]s.\n# {{lb|en|British}} A senior or supervisory [[nurse]], often in a hospital.\n#: {{syn|en|charge nurse}}\n# Any woman or girl with whom a bond is felt through the same biological sex, gender or common membership in a community, race, profession, religion, organization, or [[ism]].\n#: {{ux|en|Connie was very close to her friend Judy and considered her to be her '''sister'''.}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|year=1985|artist=w:Eurythmics; w:Aretha Franklin|album=Who’s Zoomin' Who?|title=Sisters Are Doin’ It for Themselves|passage='''Sisters''' are doing it for themselves / Standing on their own two feet}}\n# {{lb|en|AAVE|slang|sometimes|capitalized}} A [[black woman#Noun|black woman]].\n#* {{RQ:Noire Thug-A-Licious|page=169|passage=A fly '''sister''' rolled in with a suitcase full of hip-hop novels called ''The Glamorous Life'', and an African brother with long dreads wanted to sell them some incense and some fake Jacob watches.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2009|author=Rajen Persaud|title=Why Black Men Love White Women|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9781416595427|page={{gbooks|vxpSZbw6IwkC|171}}\n|passage=The short “naps” of the average '''Sister''' do not sway in the wind as that of a blonde.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2014|author=J. L. King|title=Full Circle: Loving. Living. Life. After The Down Low\n|passage=And now, social media has made it worse. From Facebook to Twitter, I get all kinds of invitations. Recently a '''sister''' inboxed me on Facebook and told me that she knew for a fact that I wanted her and she wanted me.}}\n# {{lb|en|informal}} {{n-g|A form of address to a woman.}}\n#: {{syn|en|darling|dear|love|lady|q4=US|miss|pet|q6=northern UK}}\n#: {{ux|en|What’s up, '''sister'''?}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1932|year_published=1965|author=w:Delos W. Lovelace|title=[[w:King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]]|page=13|passage=\"Listen, '''sister'''. I've got a job for you.\"}}\n# A female fellow member of a [[religious]] community, [[church]], trades union etc.\n#: {{ux|en|Thank you, '''sister'''. I would like to thank the '''sister''' who just spoke.}}\n# {{lb|en|attributively}} An entity that has a special or [[affectionate]], non-hierarchical relationship with another.\n#: {{syn|en|affiliate|affiliated}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''sister''' publication}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''sister''' city}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''sister''' projects}}\n# {{lb|en|comptheory}} A [[node]] in a [[data structure]] that shares its [[parent]] with another node.\n# {{lb|en|usually|attributively}} Something in the same class.\n#: {{ux|en|'''sister''' ships}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''sister''' facility}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Dennis W. Stevenson; Jerrold I. Davis; John V. Freudenstein; Christopher R. Hardy; Mark P. Simmons; Chelsea D. Specht|chapter=A phylogenetic analysis of the monocotyledons based on morphological and molecular character sets, with comments on the placement of ''Acorus'' and Hydatellaceae|editors=[[w:Karen Louise Wilson|Karen L[ouise] Wilson]]; David A. Morrison|title=Monocots: Systematics and Evolution|location=Collingwood, Vic.|publisher=w:CSIRO Publishing|year=2000|page=21|column=1|isbn=0 643 06437 0|passage=Within the ABCZ clade, Arecanae are '''sister''' of a group that includes all of the other taxa, and the latter fall into two major clades.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=[[w:Linguistics (journal)|Linguistics]]|issue=401|year=2006|page=11|passage=Karimi (1999) and Cheng et al. (1997), among others, on the other hand, assume that specific objects are base-generated at SpecVP, whereas nonspecific objects are '''sister''' of V.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:Bruce Beehler|Bruce M. Beehler]]; Thane K. Pratt|title=Birds of New Guinea: Distribution, Taxonomy, and Systematics|location=Princeton, N.J.; Woodstock, Oxon|publisher=w:Princeton University Press|year=2016|page=220|isbn=978-0-691-16424-3|passage=The bee-eaters are '''sister''' to a clade that includes the rollers, ground-rollers, todies, motmots, and kingfishers (Cracraft 2013).}}\n# One of two [[tornado]]s that form in close [[proximity]] at the same time or in quick [[succession]].\n\n====Usage notes====\n* In [[Roman Catholicism]], a distinction is often drawn (especially by members of female [[religious order]]s) between nuns and sisters, the former being cloistered and devoted primarily to prayer, the latter being more active, doing work such as operating hospitals, caring for the poor, or teaching.\n* The plural {{m|en|sistren}} is no longer commonly used for biological sisters in contemporary English (although it was in the past) but may be found in some religious, feminist, or poetic usage.\n\n====Coordinate terms====\n* {{l|en|brother}}\n* {{l|en|brethren}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|foresister|godsister|half sister|intersister|mersister|nonsister|pegasister|sistercest|sisterdom|sisterfucking|sistergirl|sisterji|sisterkin|sisterkins|sisterless|sisterlike|sisterlocks|sistership|sisterson|supersister|unsister\n|3/4 sister\n|baby sister\n|big sister|Big Sister\n|blood sister\n|cister\n|co-sister\n|co-sister-in-law\n|cousin-sister\n|cousin sister\n|Five Sisters\n|foster sister\n|frail sister\n|full-sisterlaw\n|half-sister\n|kid sister\n|kiss your sister|foresister|godsister|half sister|intersister|mersister|nonsister|pegasister|sistercest|sisterdom|sisterfucking|sistergirl|sisterji|sisterkin|sisterkins|sisterless|sisterlike|sisterlocks|sistership|sisterson|supersister|unsister\n|little sister\n|milk-sister\n|milk sister|Scotch sister\n|my sister in Christ\n|older sister\n|Pavlof Sister\n|scissor sister\n|Seven Sisters\n|sis\n|sissy\n|sister act\n|sister block\n|sister chromatid\n|sister chromatid cohesion\n|sister city\n|sister clip\n|sister company\n|sister from another mister\n|sister-german\n|sisterhood\n|sister hook\n|sister humper\n|sister-in-arms\n|sister in Christ\n|sister-in-law\n|sister language\n|sisterly\n|Sister Minor\n|Sister Minoress\n|sister minoress\n|sister of Eve\n|sister-out-law\n|sister planet\n|sister republic\n|sisters before misters\n|sister ship\n|sister wife\n|sister-wife\n|sob sister\n|soul sister\n|stepsister\n|three-quarter sister\n|Three Sisters\n|ugly sister\n|weak sister\n|weird sister\n|White Sister\n|younger sister|sister's thread\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|en|sororal}}\n* {{l|en|sistren}}\n* {{l|en|suster}}\n* {{l|en|sustah}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|bor=1|afb|سِسْتَر|tr=sistar|t=female nurse}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|ja|シスター|tr=shisutā}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|ko|시스터}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{see translation subpage|Noun}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive|construction}} To [[strengthen]] (a supporting [[beam]]) by fastening a second beam alongside it.\n#: {{ux|en|I’m trying to correct my sagging floor by '''sistering''' the [[joist]]s.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete|transitive}} To be [[#Noun|sister]] to; to resemble closely.\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Pericles|V|1|text=Deep clerks she dumbs; and with her needle composes<br>Nature's own shape, of bud, bird, branch, or berry,<br>That even her art '''sisters''' the natural roses;<br>Her inkle, silk, twin with the rubied cherry}}\n{{rfi|en|construction sense}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|strengthen by fastening a second beam alongside}}\n* German: {{t|de|aufdoppeln}}, {{t+|de|verstärken}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to resemble closely}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{pedia|Sister (disambiguation)}}\n* {{R:Britannica 1911|Sister}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=eirsst|Istres|Reists|reists|resist|resits|restis|risest}}\n\n{{cln|en|endearing terms|terms of address}}\n{{C|en|Female family members|Monasticism|Limenitidine butterflies}}\n{{cln|en|nouns with irregular plurals}}\n{{c|en|Weather}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|enm|noun}}\n\n# {{alt form|enm|suster}}\n\n==Scots==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|sco|:inh|enm:suster}}\nFrom {{inh|sco|enm|sister}}, {{m|enm|syster}}, forms of {{m|enm|suster}} influenced by {{cog|non|systir}}, from {{inh|sco|ang|sweostor}}, {{m|ang|swustor}}, {{m|ang|sweoster}}, from {{inh|sco|gem-pro|*swestēr}}, from {{inh|sco|ine-pro|*swésōr}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|sco|[ˈsɪstər]}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sco-noun|pl=sisteris}}\n\n# {{l|en|sister}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|sco|guid-sister}}\n\n{{topics|sco|Family|Female}}"}}